<h3>PASSPORT</h3>
<p>Important:<em> Please check your passport to ensure that it has minimum 6 months validity beyond your date of entry, as this is required to enter the country of Indonesia. For social visa the passport must be valid for minimum 12 months.</em> Immigration officials tend to be strict about these requirements.</p>
<h3>AIRPORT PICK-UP</h3>
<p>Getting from the Airport to Ubud by car will take around 1.5 hours. The taxi rate is IDR 300,000 (approx. 23 USD). You can pre-book one of our trusted taxi drivers ahead by whatsapp. Please provide your name, your date and time of arrival, airline, flight number and location of last departure. Also be sure to have the name and adress of the hotel you will be staying at.</p>
<p>Made +62 819 9917 8237</p>
<p>Raditya + 62 818 0363 5408</p>
<h3>CURRENCY</h3>
<p>The currency is Indonesian Rupiah (IDR). <br /> USD 1 = IDR 14,000 (approximately)</p>
<p>ATMs are available in Ubud, usually with withdrawal fees using foreign bank cards. Beware of skimmers and rigged units. There are also many foreign exchange kiosks at the airport and in Ubud. It is recommended to always count the money you receive and double check with your own calculator that it is the correct exchange rate. Major hotels, restaurants and shops accept credit cards. A few percent handeling charge is often added. The exchange rate at the time of using the card in Bali may be different from when it is billed to you in your country.</p>
<p>You&rsquo;ll find there is often one price for locals and one price for tourists in Bali, but if you&rsquo;re savvy you can barter for something in between.</p>
<h3>LANGUAGE</h3>
<p>There are two native languages in Bali. The official language is Indonesian, while the local language is Balinese. At hotels and major tourist sites, there are staff capable of speaking English.<br /> </p>
<p>LOCAL NAMES<br /> There are a lot of Wayans. All Balinese share the same four names - Wayan, Kadek, Nyoman or Ketut &ndash; whether they're male or female, and are named by order of birth. If a family has a fifth child, they will start again and call him or her Wayan. It can cause quite some confusion, but most Balinese will have a nickname so they can be distinguished. </p>
