<h3>TRANSPORTATION</h3>
<p>Driving in Bali is on the left side, a bit chaotic and unpredictable, with narrow roads, few side-walks, not many road signs, and plenty of chickens and dogs on the road. You see many people on scooters and mopeds, and If you wish rent a scooter to get around the price is about IDR 60,000 (less than 5 USD) per day. If you don't like driving yourself there is moped-taxi (gojek) which is very affordable. If you prefer the safer alternative, it is recommended to go by car. There are plenty of taxi drivers offering their services on call. I recommend to negotiate the price beforehand.</p>
<p>It is possible to rent a car without a driver and drive on your own (you need international driving license), but it's not much cheaper than hiring a car with driver. <br /> </p>
<h3>INSURANCE AND SAFETY</h3>
<p>There are a few cases of pickpockets and purse-snatching. When you go out, don&rsquo;t take all valuables with you and when you walk on the sidewalks, don&rsquo;t carry your bag on the road side. Don&rsquo;t leave cards or cash accessible. Keep valuables, including your passport and cash, in the safety deposit box at your hotel.<br /> <br /> Just in case there are any unexpected unfortunate events such as illness or having your belongings stolen, we recommend you to get overseas accident insurance before departing your country.</p>
<p>It is recommended to make copies of your passport, travel insurance, and other important travel documents. Should you loose your passport, having a photocopy of it will greatly expedite getting a replacement from an embassy in Asia.</p>
<h3>WATER</h3>
<p>Drink filtered water only, and brush your teeth in it too. Many hotels and resorts provide complimentary filtered water.</p>
<h3>CLIMATE</h3>
<p>Bali has a tropical monsoon climate. April to September is the dry season and October to March, the rainy season. However, rainy season will vary and is not predictable. The most rain comes between December and February. <br /> </p>
<p>ELECTRICAL PLUGS<br /> Electricity in Bali is 230 Volts, 50Hz. If the standard voltage in your country is between 220V - 240V you can use your electric appliances in Indonesia. Electrical plugs are two-pronged &lsquo;Europlug&rsquo; type. The pins are round, not flat or rectangular. If you come from Australia, Japan, USA, Malaysia, UK, Canada, Singapore, and some countries in Africa you will most likely need a plug adapter otherwise the plugs for your electrical appliances will not fit into the Bali Socket. You can easily find an adapter at all international airports, and also in Bali they are commonly found in many shops for a few dollars. </p>
