<h3>MEDICATION</h3>
<p>Hopefully it won&rsquo;t be needed, but walk-in pharmacies sell nearly everything in terms of first-aid, medicine and even prescription drugs.</p>
<h3>LAUNDRY</h3>
<p>You'll find plenty of places that do laundry for a small fee based on weight.</p>
<h3>WHAT TO BRING:</h3>
<p><strong>Note book and pens</strong> for taking notes at class</p>
<p><strong>Mosquito repellent</strong><br /> <strong>Flip-flops or sandals</strong> that can tolerate to get wet<br /> <strong>Light clothes</strong> in natural, breathable fabrics. Even in the upmarket restaurants it&rsquo;s still pretty casual.</p>
<p><strong>Swim suit </strong></p>
<p><strong>Rain coat or umbrella </strong></p>
<p><strong>Sarong</strong> is needed if you want to enter any Hindu temples and sacred sites</p>
<p><strong>Flash light</strong> for unexpected power outages &ndash; quite a common occurrence in Bali</p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>Most of these items are sold in Bali, so in case you prefer to travel light, or if you forget something it is easy to purchase these common items after you arrive. </strong></p>
